					<description><![CDATA[<p>Mine these insights from 10 successful marketers for a more successful 2025.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/2025-marketing-tips">How to Thrive in 2025: 10 Marketing Pros Give Their Top Tips</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>A lot has changed since last December. SERPs look different. Attribution doesn‚Äôt work the same way it used to. And, of course, AI has somehow made marketing easier, harder, better, and worse all at the same time.</p>
<p>I was curious what other marketers think it all means for the next 12 months. So, I asked 10 experienced marketers for their top marketing tips going into 2025.</p>
<p>No surprise, there were several mentions of AI, but not in the way I expected. It wasn‚Äôt about bigger, faster, cheaper. The throughline was a return to providing unique points of view, personal experiences, and original data to stand above the oncoming torrent of mass-produced mass communication. And even using AI to help beat AI content.</p>
<p>If you‚Äôre about to put pencil to marketing plan, consider these top marketing tips for 2025 from the pros.</p>
<h3>Contents</h3>
<ol>
<li><a href="#embrace-negative-reviews">Embrace negative reviews</a></li>
<li><a href="#create-what-ai-cant">Create what AI can‚Äôt</a></li>
<li><a href="#think-outside-the-blog-for-seo-success">Think outside the blog for SEO success</a></li>
<li><a href="#empower-your-internal-influencers">Empower your internal influencers</a></li>
<li><a href="#expand-your-marketing-channels">Expand your marketing channels</a></li>
<li><a href="#train-ai-t0-write-like-you">Train AI to write like you</a></li>
<li><a href="#focus-on-solving-problems">Focus on solving problems</a></li>
<li><a href="#make-a-marketing-moat-with-customer-insights">Make a marketing moat with customer insights</a></li>
<li><a href="#break-through-selective-attention">Break through selective attention</a></li>
<li><a href="#leave-negative-space-in-your-campaign">Leave negative space in your campaigns</a></li>
</ol>
<h2>10 best marketing tips for 2025</h2>
<p>These marketing tips aren‚Äôt just good advice. They say a lot about the mood of marketers moving into the new year.</p>
<div id="embrace-negative-reviews"></div>
<h3>1. Embrace negative reviews</h3>
<p>A perfect five-star rating sounds pretty awesome. But <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/allenfinn/">Allen Finn</a>, VP of Marketing at <a href="https://www.heatmap.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">heatmap</a>, said those <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/how-to-respond-to-negative-reviews/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">less-than-stellar reviews</a> are critical to revenue growth.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Expert-marketing-tips-negative-review.webp" alt="Expert marketing tips - screenshot of a negative review." width="827" height="345" class="aligncenter wp-image-87367 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Expert-marketing-tips-negative-review.webp 827w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Expert-marketing-tips-negative-review-480x200.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 827px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Bad reviews hurt, but Allen Finn of </em><a href="https://www.heatmap.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>heatmap</em></a><em> says they‚Äôre also good for business.</em></p>
<p>‚ÄúEcomm brands showcasing one-star reviews are driving 40% more revenue than those hiding behind five stars,‚Äù he said.</p>
<p>That‚Äôs a pretty counterintuitive conclusion, and Allen brought the receipts.</p>
<p>‚ÄúThe heatmap team analyzed the review and testimonial sections of 50,000+ ecommerce websites,‚Äù he explained. ‚ÄúWhat we found was shocking: Users who click on one-star reviews drive about 40% more revenue than users who click on four and five-star reviews.‚Äù</p>
<p>Allen said one-star reviews paradoxically <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/how-online-reviews-impact-your-business">improve conversion rates</a> for several reasons:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Authenticity:</strong> ‚ÄúThe presence of negative reviews suggests that the feedback is genuine and unfiltered, enhancing overall trust in the brand&#8217;s transparency.‚Äù</li>
<li><strong>Expectation management:</strong> ‚ÄúNegative reviews can highlight potential issues, allowing customers to set realistic expectations and reduce post-purchase dissatisfaction.‚Äù</li>
<li><strong>Trust in positive reviews:</strong> ‚ÄúThe existence of negative reviews lends more credibility to the positive ones, as it suggests that all feedback is published, not just favorable reviews.‚Äù</li>
</ul>
<p>The study results highlight the ‚Äúpower of authenticity,‚Äù Allen said. ‚ÄúNegative reviews can significantly contribute to building consumer confidence and, ultimately, improving revenue.‚Äù</p>
<p>Of course, it‚Äôs not a great idea to ruin customer relationships in hopes of nabbing some negative feedback. But when you do get a critical review, use it as a learning experience, and don‚Äôt try to cover it up. It may just be the revenue boost you‚Äôre looking for.</p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f4a1.png" alt="üí°" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>Want more?</strong> Download <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/resources/online-marketing-tips?cid=Web_WS_InContent_Guide_130marketingtips_Download">130+ of the Best Online Marketing Tips for Generating More Traffic, Leads, &amp; Sales</a>.</p>
<div id="create-what-ai-cant"></div>
<h3>2. Create what AI can‚Äôt</h3>
<p>The commoditization of content started long before AI hit the scene.¬†But <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ai-copywriting-tools">AI copywriting tools</a> in the wrong hands have hastened the race to SEO sameness. <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/kristianarule/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Kristiana Rule</a>, a content strategy consultant, said the best marketers will rise above the digital noise in 2025 by creating things AI can‚Äôt.</p>
<p>‚ÄúWith so much generic AI content flooding the internet in 2024, the demand for something more authentic will likely increase in 2025,‚Äù Kristiana said. ‚ÄúLean into creating memorable, specific, and useful content for your audience.‚Äù</p>
<p>Original studies are high on Kristiana&#8217;s list of content to focus on in 2025. We previously got a similar rec from <a href="https://www.beamcontent.co/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Beam Content‚Äôs</a> co-founder, <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/brooklin-nash/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Brooklyn Nash</a>. He has a strategy for using one set of original data to fuel months‚Äô worth of unique content (which you can <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/how-marketing-pros-drive-traffic">read about here</a>).</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Expert-marketing-tips-beam.webp" alt="Expert marketing tips - screenshot from Beam report." width="875" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-87368 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Expert-marketing-tips-beam.webp 875w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Expert-marketing-tips-beam-480x329.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 875px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Original content, like this report created by Beam Content, is the counterweight to generic AI output, Kristiana Rule said.</em></p>
<p>Kristiana also suggests writing with a distinct <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/07/31/brand-voice">brand voice</a> and creating bottom-of-funnel (BOFU) content that‚Äôs based on ‚Äúactual customer questions vs. keywords.‚Äù Those things will become the audiences‚Äô Turing Test to tell whether something was created by human hands or built by a bot.</p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f913.png" alt="ü§ì" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /><strong> The best marketing tip of all is to plan ahead.</strong> Use <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/resources/marketing-calendar?cid=Web_WS_InContent_Guide_2025MarketingCalendar_Download&amp;itm_source=wordstream&amp;itm_medium=blog&amp;itm_campaign=incontent_links">The Only Marketing Calendar You Need for 2025</a> to make it easy.</p>
<div id="think-outside-the-blog-for-seo-success"></div>
<h3>3. Think outside the blog for SEO success</h3>
<p>Informational SERPs aren‚Äôt just a list of links to blog posts anymore. <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/krisettecapati/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Krisette Lim</a>, a content marketing specialist with <a href="https://appetiser.com.au/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Appetiser Apps</a>, said if you want <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/seo">SEO success</a> in 2025, you‚Äôll need to think beyond the blog.</p>
<p>‚ÄúIn 2025 and beyond, SEO and <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/07/13/content-marketing-strategy">content marketing</a> will cover a broad spectrum of channels where your brand is represented‚Äîfrom websites to social media and community forums,‚Äù she pointed out. ‚ÄúSearch on Google will capture these touchpoints‚Äînot just your website‚Äîas <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/04/28/user-generated-content">user-generated content (UGC)</a> becomes more prominent on search results.‚Äù</p>
<p>Here‚Äôs an illustration of Krisette‚Äôs point. Try searching something like ‚ÄúHow do I get out of a shadowban.‚Äù Below the AI overview and ‚ÄúPeople Also Ask‚Äù feature, you‚Äôll see results from <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/google-ads-smart-bidding">Reddit</a>, Quora, and YouTube. That&#8217;s because SERPs now surface snippets from social media sites, online forums, and video platforms.</p>
<p>If you‚Äôre the one answering that question on those platforms, you‚Äôll garner some <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2015/07/10/brand-awareness">brand awareness</a> and have more shots at SERP placements.</p>
<p>But even if that‚Äôs not in your bandwidth, Krisette suggests mining these topical troves for content ideas. ‚ÄúRead and listen to people&#8217;s questions on these forums and answer them on your blog,‚Äù she said. That‚Äôs a sure-fire way to publish posts people want to read and search engines want to promote.</p>
<div id="empower-your-internal-influencers"></div>
<h3>4. Empower your internal influencers</h3>
<p>If you post <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/types-of-social-media-content/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">social media content</a> on your brand‚Äôs account, you know how tough of a slog it can be to grow organic engagement. Most people don‚Äôt feel connected enough to a faceless brand to drop a comment or even tap ‚Äúlike.‚Äù</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">As <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/briannefleming/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Brianne Fleming</a>, author of the marketing newsletter <a href="https://briannefleming.com/newsletter/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">By Popular Demand</a>, put it, ‚ÄúWe connect with faces, not logos.‚Äù</p>
<p>That‚Äôs why her top marketing tip for 2025 is to help your employees step out from behind the logo, especially on LinkedIn. &#8220;LinkedIn is having a moment, and your employees are your biggest influencers. Hearing from the people behind a company is the best way to humanize it,‚Äù Brianne said.</p>
<p>While individual results will vary, I can vouch for how this works. When I share a content link from my personal LinkedIn account, it gets as much or more engagement as a similar post on our business account. And I have way fewer followers than the company page has.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Expert-marketing-tips-linkedin2.webp" alt="Expert marketing tips - LinkedIn post screenshot." width="537" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-87385 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Expert-marketing-tips-linkedin2.webp 537w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Expert-marketing-tips-linkedin2-480x536.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 537px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>The </em><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/posts/rob-c-glover_can-you-double-your-conversion-rate-by-simply-activity-7259570168677203969-JVe7?utm_source=share&amp;utm_medium=member_desktop" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>repost</em></a><em> on my personal LinkedIn page accounted for nearly 80% of the total impressions for this content.</em></p>
<p>Brianne says the trick is that you can‚Äôt just ask or force your people to become instant influencers. ‚ÄúEmpower your teams to share their thoughts and proudly celebrate their work.&#8221; That means helping them use the opportunity to <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/personal-branding-on-linkedin/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">build their personal network</a> and become thought leaders in their own right. Give them content and topics to share. And maybe even create post templates so it‚Äôs less of a burden to stay on brand.</p>
<div id="expand-your-marketing-channels"></div>
<h3>5. Expand your marketing channels</h3>
<p>Have a scroll through <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/bakerseo/">Jeff Baker‚Äôs LinkedIn feed</a>. Tucked in amongst the industry trends and <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/posts/bakerseo_taco-bell-brings-back-nostalgic-fan-favorites-activity-7260669751306133504-F6GS?utm_source=share&amp;utm_medium=member_desktop">Taco Bell takes</a>, you‚Äôll see frequent callouts to subscribe to his <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/newsletters/7247014071105925121/?displayConfirmation=true">Work From Anywhere Job Alerts</a> newsletter. He chose to house and promote the newsletter on LinkedIn instead of through the traditional blog and SEO strategy.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Expert-marketing-tips-newsletter.webp" alt="Expert marketing tips - Screenshot of Jeff Baker's LinkedIn post." width="577" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-87371 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Expert-marketing-tips-newsletter.webp 577w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Expert-marketing-tips-newsletter-480x499.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 577px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Jeff publishes his newsletter natively on LinkedIn, which lets him avoid the volatility of search algorithms.</em></p>
<p>Even as an experienced fractional SEO consultant (and fractional CMO), Jeff said the money move in 2025 is to explore beyond search. ‚ÄúWith the <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/local-seo-in-2024">volatility we are seeing in search due to algorithm changes</a>, AI Overviews, and ChatGPT, it&#8217;s going to be more important than ever for marketers to expand their channels.‚Äù</p>
<p>And which channel did Jeff suggest marketers focus on in 2025? Good old-fashioned <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/07/01/email-marketing-tips">email marketing</a>. ‚ÄúIf you have a large enough email list, you‚Äôll be able to sell your products and services, period.‚Äù</p>
<p><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/08/05/increase-email-signups#:~:text=Put%20up%20an%20email%20signup,in%20exchange%20for%20a%20resource.">Growing your email list</a> takes time. But when it becomes your goal, you‚Äôll start seeing all sorts of ways to do it. Here are a few of the ways I‚Äôve seen brands speed that process up:</p>
<ul>
<li>Run a contest or <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/giveaway-ideas">giveaway</a>.</li>
<li>Offer <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/06/15/lead-magnet-ideas">lead magnets</a> like big content assets.</li>
<li>Put subscription forms in page popups, sidebars, headers, and footers.</li>
<li>Ask new customers to sign up and incentivize them to<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/04/14/referral-program-ideas"> invite friends</a>.</li>
</ul>
<p>Instead of trying to wring more site visits from an unstable traffic source, consider Jeff‚Äôs advice and invest those resources in building an audience on a platform you have more control over. ‚ÄúI would take 10K email addresses over 100K visitors per month.‚Äù</p>
<div id="train-ai-t0-write-like-you"></div>
<h3>6. Train your AI to write like you</h3>
<p>AI isn‚Äôt going away. Nor should it. You can gain so much efficiency‚Äîand free yourself up for more creativity‚Äîby letting your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ai-tools-for-marketing-agency">AI tools</a> shoulder repetitive work.</p>
<p>But you can‚Äôt just throw in an <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ai-prompts">AI prompt</a> and expect to get a marketing asset that stands out from the rest of the robo-content, said <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ehtisham-hussain-0b12b860/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Ehtisham Hussain</a>, a <a href="https://www.ehtishamhussain.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">fractional head of marketing</a> with AI experience. ‚ÄúYour competitors will flood the internet with AI-generated written, audio, and video content like never before.‚Äù</p>
<p>Ehtisham reckons you don‚Äôt need to ditch AI to be different. ‚ÄúYour biggest challenge will be making your content rise above the noise. To do that, I recommend training your AI tools on past, human-written content that embodies your voice and <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/how-to-create-a-brand-identity/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">brand identity</a>.‚Äù</p>
<p>We‚Äôve seen people cajole AI into writing like <a href="https://www.zdnet.com/article/i-used-chatgpt-to-rewrite-my-text-in-the-style-of-shakespeare-c3po-and-harry-potter/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Shakespeare and C3PO</a>. It can because it has content in those voices to train it. You probably have lots of content in your preferred style. Ehtisham suggested feeding it to your AI copywriter. ‚ÄúBy doing so, you will get your AI tools to produce new content in your voice and style,‚Äù he said.</p>
<p>Once you have your AI co-writer thinking like you, Ehtisham said to apply it to content others aren&#8217;t writing. ‚ÄúLean heavily into POV-driven content. Everyone will do the AI-generated &#8216;what, why, how&#8217; pieces, and they will all sound the same. Your real stories, opinions, and advice based on personal experiences will give you a better chance of standing out.&#8221;</p>
<div id="focus-on-solving-problems"></div>
<h3>7. Focus on solving problems</h3>
<p>Your customers are arguably busier and more distracted than ever. <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/goranmirkovic/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Goran Mirkovic</a>, Chief Marketing Officer at <a href="https://freemius.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Freemius</a>, said next year will be all about exposing value over describing products.</p>
<p>‚ÄúIn 2025, B2B SaaS marketing needs to continue to shift from ‚Äòhere‚Äôs our product‚Äô to ‚Äòhere‚Äôs how we can help you succeed,‚Äô‚Äù Goran said. ‚ÄúAt Freemius, we‚Äôve seen firsthand how content that focuses on solving problems, not just showcasing features, builds real trust with our audience.‚Äù</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Expert-marketing-tips-freemius.webp" alt="Expert marketing tips - screenshot from Freemius website." width="908" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-87372 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Expert-marketing-tips-freemius.webp 908w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Expert-marketing-tips-freemius-480x317.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 908px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://freemius.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Freemius‚Äô website copy</em></a><em> leads with benefits and clearly calls out who can use them.</em></p>
<p>At ground level, that means content and <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2019/09/03/copywriting-examples">marketing copy</a> that hyper-focuses on your customers&#8217; challenges, Goran said. And then going the extra mile to give them real actions they can take to solve them.</p>
<p>He added that marketing that leads with <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/customer-pain-points/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">customer challenges</a> will help people find and trust your business. ‚ÄúAs search engines prioritize expertise, thought leadership pieces, case studies, customer stories, and how-to guides will rise above the noise. And they position your brand as a go-to resource.‚Äù</p>
<p>Goran explained that this is less of a tactic or strategy than a mindset you have to apply to all your campaigns. ‚ÄúFor us, it‚Äôs not about convincing customers to buy‚Äîit&#8217;s about earning their trust over time by showing we understand their needs and are here to help.&#8221;</p>
<div id="make-a-marketing-moat-with-customer-insights"></div>
<h3>8. Make a marketing moat with customer insights</h3>
<p>The best marketers have always used <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2020/01/24/customer-feedback">customer feedback</a> to guide decisions. Unfortunately, there are precious few opportunities to sit and chat with a customer. <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/stella-inabo-/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Stella Inabo</a>, a Content Marketer at <a href="https://www.float.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Float</a>, said you may already have all the customer intel you need.</p>
<p>‚ÄúIt is hard to get people to agree to a 30-minute chat. Instead of opting for direct conversations, I‚Äôve found reading transcripts or watching video recordings from past customer interactions to be a good substitute.‚Äù</p>
<p>Diving into customer interactions will help <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/10/27/brand-messaging">make your messaging more relevant</a>. But the real gold is that it can create a marketing moat other businesses can&#8217;t cross. ‚ÄúNone of our competitors have access to this information, so it made our articles unique,‚Äù Stella explained.</p>
<p>For example, Stella said she recently conducted a series of customer interviews. The initial goal was to <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2017/04/03/how-to-write-a-case-study">publish case studies</a> and move on to the next job. ‚ÄúHowever, as I rewatched the recordings, I realized they held so many insights into our audience,‚Äù she said.</p>
<p>Stella listed a few of the takeaways from those interactions and how she used them:</p>
<ul>
<li>Their pain points became article and <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/how-to-host-a-webinar/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">webinar</a> topics.</li>
<li>Their workarounds for problems highlighted objections to address.</li>
<li>Their processes provided expert tips for how-to articles.</li>
<li>Their language helped shape the <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/01/13/best-words-and-phrases-for-marketing">words and phrases</a> on our homepage and in customer-facing content.</li>
</ul>
<p>Where else can you find these hidden collections of customer comments? Try sales call recordings, onboarding documents, and customer service tickets/recordings.</p>
<p>‚ÄúDepending on the questions asked, you can use these internal assets to find out who your customers are, what they need, how they buy, and where they go for information,‚Äù Stella said. ‚ÄúJust to be safe, you should definitely check in with your customers to ensure it‚Äôs okay to use their words and ideas in articles.‚Äù</p>
<div id="break-through-selective-attention"></div>
<h3>9. Break through selective attention</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/colby-flood/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Colby Flood</a>, Founder at <a href="https://www.brighterclick.com/ugc-agency" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Brighter Click</a>, said that in 2025, marketers will need to really think about what they post on social media.</p>
<p>‚ÄúPeople are on social media to find content that entertains, educates, or connects with them emotionally and will likely filter out everything else due to what we call ‚Äú<a href="https://osheenjain.medium.com/science-of-selective-attention-how-we-filter-information-and-why-it-matters-644582c9e844" target="_blank" rel="noopener">selective attention</a>,‚Äù he said.</p>
<p>Selective attention is our brains‚Äô defense mechanism against being overwhelmed in buzzy environments. It‚Äôs how we filter out the drone of a city street but can hear a favorite song from half a block away. It‚Äôs also how we can scroll through a dozen posts at speed and automatically stop on one that interests us.</p>
<p>So, how do we stop speedy scrollers?</p>
<p>‚ÄúLean into UGC and influencer content to craft authentic, engaging ads,‚Äù Colby said. ‚ÄúConsider ways to naturally incorporate your product into stories or scenarios that resonate with your target audience.‚Äù</p>
<p><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2020/02/13/ugc-instagram">User-generated content works well</a> because it‚Äôs peer-to-peer marketing. The content creator will naturally hit themes that resonate with other people like them.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Expert-marketing-tips-UGC-1.webp" alt="Expert marketing tips - UGC social media post." width="329" height="566" class="aligncenter wp-image-87373 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Expert-marketing-tips-UGC-1.webp 329w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Expert-marketing-tips-UGC-1-174x300.webp 174w" sizes="(max-width: 329px) 100vw, 329px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>UGC features people relevant to your target audience, cutting through their selective attention.</em></p>
<p>Don‚Äôt stress out trying to be the next GoPro of user-generated content. Here are a few easy ways you can turn product users into social media content creators for your brand:</p>
<ul>
<li>Add user-generated FAQs to your website and share them on social media.</li>
<li>Post snippets from <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/03/03/testimonial-advertising">user testimonials</a>.</li>
<li>Promote your reviews.</li>
<li>Ask users to add a branded hashtag like #[product]results when they post about the great things they‚Äôve done with your product.</li>
<li>Use <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/03/25/social-listening-boolean-search">social listening</a> to find positive conversations about your brand, then ask if you can share them on your feeds.</li>
</ul>
<p>We‚Äôre talking about marketing here, so Colby added a reminder to use those same attention-grabbing tactics to convert social scrollers. ‚ÄúCap it off with a <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/how-pros-write-calls-to-action">powerful CTA</a> that speaks directly to your audience‚Äôs needs, sparking action that feels rewarding, not forced.‚Äù</p>
<div id="leave-negative-space-in-your-campaign"></div>
<h3>10. Leave negative space in your campaigns</h3>
<p>‚ÄúNegative space‚Äù is the blank area that separates design elements on a page. It makes important text and graphics feel more important and helps viewers process the information they‚Äôre receiving.</p>
<p><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/reaserios/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Rease Rios</a>, Director of Content at <a href="https://qase.io/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Qase</a>, says that you should apply the same principle to your <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/marketing-calendar/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">marketing calendar</a>.</p>
<p>‚ÄúDon‚Äôt become white noise,‚Äù she said. ‚ÄúSpace out your big launches so your audience has time to get curious about what you‚Äôll come up with next. If you run back-to-back major campaigns all year long, you‚Äôll burn out your audience.‚Äù</p>
<p>It‚Äôs not just your audience‚Äôs attention at risk, Rease warned. ‚ÄúKnow when it‚Äôs time to push and when it‚Äôs time to rest,‚Äù she said. ‚ÄúYou‚Äôll also burn out your team. They need room to be creative.‚Äù</p>
<p>The right cadence depends a lot on your business, especially its size and structure. One large campaign a quarter is a great goal for most, though. That allows time to gather results from a few tactics (like repurposing) that‚Äôll inform the next big campaign.</p>
<h2>The main marketing tip for 2025: Connect authentically</h2>
<p>I didn‚Äôt use AI to write this article, but if I had, this is where it would say, ‚ÄúIn the quickly evolving landscape of marketing, you‚Äôll need new strategies and ideas to succeed.‚Äù And it wouldn‚Äôt be wrong.</p>
<p>Just a few years ago, none of us probably thought that Google would use AI to shove our links further down the page. We couldn‚Äôt imagine spinning up a dozen clone articles to heist SERP spots. Nor would we guess at the dramatic changes in how Twitter (ahem‚Ä¶X), Facebook, and TikTok operate.</p>
<p>But what‚Äôs interesting to me is that the marketing tips I got weren‚Äôt a bunch of complex, technical processes to hijack algorithms or game Google Ads. They all described some version of making marketing more human, which makes sense. No matter how many tech tools we throw at the job, we‚Äôre still people selling to people.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/2025-marketing-tips-wordstream.webp" alt="2025 marketing tips from experts infographic" width="378" height="1500" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-87615" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/2025-marketing-tips-wordstream.webp 378w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/2025-marketing-tips-wordstream-258x1024.webp 258w" sizes="(max-width: 378px) 100vw, 378px" /></p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/2025-marketing-tips">How to Thrive in 2025: 10 Marketing Pros Give Their Top Tips</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
